As always, the Wentworth Show offer a great family day out for visitors and locals alike highlighting country living. Displays in the magnificent Wentworth Showgrounds Community Pavilion include cookery, preserves and produce, floral art, fine arts, photography, needlework and school displays. &nbsp;

A Feast for the Senses food and wine marquee will feature a wide variety of tastings and sales for both food and wine. 

There will be Horses in action, sheep and wool displays, ute competition and shearing competitions, sheep and yard dog trials, trade exhibits and side shows. 

There's a treasure hunt to amuse the children, while the animal nursery and Meccano display are also popular. &nbsp;Junior Miss Showgirl, whip cracking and the popular dog jumping to create a special atmosphere at this unique country show; with the usual show rides and show food vans. 

This is the biggest annual event in the Wentworth Region. &nbsp;One of the nation's few remaining authentic country shows that manages to retain its rustic, rural flavour in a relaxed atmosphere whilst catering to an increasingly wide variety of tastes. &nbsp; 

For more entry information, please visit the website.

In Sowing N' Sewing Gilgandra-based artist Clementine Belle McIntosh challenges the human-centric relationships which define her inherent "sense of place". Combining textiles with traditional painting techniques and impulsive mark-marking with nonhuman collaboration, McIntosh's textile installations reflect the dynamic and complex interactions present between local environments, industries, and communities in the context of rural Australia.

A continuation of McIntosh's regenerative approach to art making, Sowing N' Sewing invites viewers to be enveloped by the textile materials utilised and consider the narratives of the land, the industry that relies on it and the people that live within it. Thus, allowing you to build your own associations towards a "sense of place".&nbsp;

This is a HomeGround exhibition, produced by the WPCC and supported by Orana Arts. HomeGround is sponsored by Wingewarra Dental.

Every weekend, experience rail travel with a&nbsp;45-minute steam train ride&nbsp;in beautifully restored carriages along the original ‘Great Southern Railway’ from Thirlmere to Buxton and return.&nbsp;

​With Australia's largest collection of heritage rolling stock, state-of-the-art facilities, interactive exhibits for children&nbsp;and so much more,&nbsp;you don't want to miss Steam Train Weekends at the NSW Rail Museum.&nbsp;

Book your tickets online today.

A garden teeming with temptation and desire, grotesque creatures and improbable scenes of surrender: the uninhibited world of Hieronymus Bosch's 500-year-old triptych "De tuin der lusten". Baffling his Dutch contemporaries and the casual tourists in Madrid's Prado in equal measure (not to mention generations of art critics) Bosch's Garden of Earthly Delights is ever-enigmatic. Whether it is interpreted as a surreal feast for the senses or as a stark warning about the moral decay during a time of rapid change, this art exudes dread and seduction in equal measure.&nbsp;

Trust Luminescence Chamber Singers to turn this surreal feast of the senses into an aural tapestry as pleasurable and perilous as Bosch's vision. Drawn from the vaults of Renaissance raunch, Medieval monasterian excess and daring modern transgressions, Garden of Earthly Delights offers a vocal cornucopia of surprise and surreptitiously cheeky delight, probing the pleasures and perils of excess.

Program to include music by Josquin, Banchieri, Gallus and new works by Nicole Murphy and Archie Tulk.

As you step into this open-air culinary oasis, the world transforms around you. The air crackles with the energy of live music, the scents of smouldering embers, and fire-wielding chefs turn local produce into a feast to be remembered. Welcome to Feast Over Fire.
&nbsp;
Feast is where the timeless art of open-flame cooking meets the pristine beauty of the Central Coast. The inaugural Feast Over Fire Long Lunch is a tribute to the region, a celebration of regenerative farming, and a culinary journey like no other.
&nbsp;
As the sun graces the horizon, the chefs kindle the fires, tending to the coals while produce hangs over open flames, sending aromatic smoke billowing into the sky. An immersive dining adventure awaits you, where you'll be enveloped by the sights, scents, and flavours of open-fire cooking. Positioned ringside at the open kitchen, you'll witness each course's transformation over hot coals and flames, using sustainably harvested wood and local charcoal. Each course is thoughtfully paired with locally produced wines, complemented by signature wild cocktails infused with native herbs, spices, and berries.
&nbsp;
Amid communal tables beneath the open sky, bringing people together turning strangers into friends. Fostering a sense of community and connection sharing an unforgettable outdoor dining experience that celebrates the region, its produce, its people, and the land.

The TCS Sydney Marathon presented by ASICS is Australia's largest marathon and the sole remaining participant legacy of the Sydney 2000 Olympic Games. Owned by Athletics Australia and managed by Pont3, the event is a 'Hallmark Event'&nbsp;supported by the NSW Government via Destination NSW.&nbsp;

In 2024, the marathon joined the prestigious Abbott World Marathon Majors, becoming one of only seven elite global marathons alongside Tokyo, Boston, London, Berlin, Chicago, and New York City.&nbsp;

The event attracts runners from over 100 countries and has raised nearly AUD30 million for charity since its inception. The event is committed to accessibility, with a growing focus on participant diversity,&nbsp;accessible venue design, and an ongoing partnership with&nbsp;Wheelchair Sport NSW.

